04256nam a22005535i 9780226135564DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013037618  a9780226135564  a(DE-B1597)523145  a(OCoLC)880827277  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aB2949.D5bC635 2014 4aB2949.D5 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a1211 aCole, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Birth of Theory /cAndrew Cole. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Very like a Whale -- tAcknowledgments -- tPART 1. Theory -- tPART 2. History -- tPART 3. Literature -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModern theory needs a history lesson. Neither Marx nor Nietzsche first gave us theory—Hegel did. To support this contention, Andrew Cole’s The Birth of Theory presents a refreshingly clear and lively account of the origins and legacy of Hegel’s dialectic as theory. Cole explains how Hegel boldly broke from modern philosophy when he adopted medieval dialectical habits of thought to fashion his own dialectic. While his contemporaries rejected premodern dialectic as outdated dogma, Hegel embraced both its emphasis on language as thought and its fascination with the categories of identity and difference, creating what we now recognize as theory, distinct from systematic philosophy. Not content merely to change philosophy, Hegel also used this dialectic to expose the persistent archaism of modern life itself, Cole shows, establishing a method of social analysis that has influenced everyone from Marx and the nineteenth-century Hegelians, to Nietzsche and Bakhtin, all the way to Deleuze and Jameson. By uncovering these theoretical filiations across time, The Birth of Theory will not only change the way we read Hegel, but also the way we think about the histories of theory. With chapters that powerfully reanimate the overly familiar topics of ideology, commodity fetishism, and political economy, along with a groundbreaking reinterpretation of Hegel’s famous master/slave dialectic, The Birth of Theory places the disciplines of philosophy, literature, and history in conversation with one another in an unprecedented way. Daring to reconcile the sworn enemies of Hegelianism and Deleuzianism, this timely book will revitalize dialectics for the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDialecticxHistory. 0aTheory (Philosophy) 0aTheory (Philosophy). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  ahegel, dialectic, modern philosophy, marx, nietzsche, language, thought, identity, difference, social theory, bakhtin, deleuze, jameson, ideology, commodity fetishism, political economy, master slave, literature, history, medieval, nicolas of cusa, plotinus, walmart, materialism, vitalism, epistemology, marxism, postmodernism, continental, premodern, feudal, lord, bondsman, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022613539740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226135564423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226135564/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles